# Global Library & Collection Standard™ (133)

**Full document:** `docs/constitution/133_GLOBAL_LIBRARY_AND_COLLECTION_STANDARD.md`

**Binding product law** for every Spark Estate experience that displays multiple user-owned records (Create, Projects, Journal, Evidence Vault, Spark Cards, Business Estate, Marketing, Founder Workspace, Learning, Documents, Conversations, future Chamber libraries, and any browse/shelf/vault/inbox).

## Constitutional principle

**If a member can reasonably perform an action without opening an item, they must be able to do so from the item’s card or list row.**

Opening is for interior work (full content, deep edit, guided flow) — not for unlocking common lifecycle actions.

## Twelve rules (summary)

1. Card/row action parity — rename, archive, favorite, export, delete(+confirm), status, continue  
2. Opening is for interior work only  
3. One primary action per card (usually Continue / Open / Resume)  
4. Honest identity on the card — title, preview, status; no architecture IDs  
5. Counts and labels tell the truth (132)  
6. Loading / empty / error all resolve calmly  
7. Search, filter, sort protect momentum  
8. Destructive actions confirmed with hospitality language  
9. Connection-gated actions honest; incompatible destinations never shown just because connected  
10. Same mental model across rooms — local flavor OK, new grammar not  
11. ADHD / EF first — Continue obvious; don’t bury common actions  
12. Estate language — not file-manager / dataset jargon  

## Before shipping any multi-record library (all must pass)

- [ ] Common actions available from card/row without opening?  
- [ ] One primary action obvious in ten seconds (132)?  
- [ ] Secondary actions in progressive disclosure (≤3 visible choices)?  
- [ ] Title + preview + status answer “what is this?” without opening?  
- [ ] Counts / filters truthful?  
- [ ] Loading / empty / error resolve?  
- [ ] Destructive confirm with Shari voice?  
- [ ] No silent no-op on gated actions?  
- [ ] Pattern matches other Estate libraries?  
- [ ] Passes 128 ADHD / simplicity audit?  

## Conflict rules

- **128** wins on complexity / architecture exposure / ADHD certification  
- **130** One Creation Rule — never silently create Work  
- **132** wins on momentum, intentional navigation, truthfulness, Ten-Second Rule  
- **133** governs library/collection card-row interaction  

